    "content": "# 2026-04-20\n\n## Canonical business context interview with Debbie\nDebbie asked for an in-depth canonical interview to serve as the source of truth for future strategic and business-aligned work. Key context captured:\n\n- Debbie is Operations Manager for the polo events business. She handles marquee sales, customer liaison, ticketing admin, invoicing, sponsorship admin, and supplier coordination.\n- Business operates established NZ events in Christchurch and Auckland, newer Australian events in Sydney and Portsea, with Brisbane planned and Melbourne possible. Singapore is on hold while they try to secure ponies.\n- Core team: Simon Wilson (MD), Debbie, Francesca Morelli (marketing and ticketing), plus Sam Hopkinson as Sydney-based Polo Director and extra contractors for event delivery.\n- Business is rapidly growing.\n- Core revenue pillars are sponsorship, private marquee corporate hospitality, VIP tickets, and GA tickets.\n- Sponsorship is sold year-round, with a mix of annual and multi-year deals. Private marquees sell as soon as dates launch. VIP and GA launch together after sponsorship and marquees. Biggest cash flow squeeze is immediately after events when supplier invoices land.\n- Hardest sales: team sponsorships. Most predictable in NZ: marquee sales.\n- Long-term ambition: be the number 1 sporting and lifestyle event in NZ and Australia, premium, iconic, culturally relevant, exclusive, globally recognised, selling out in the first week.\n- Growth goals include more Australian cities, possible USA cities, doubled sponsorship revenue, multi-day events in some markets, stronger recurring sponsorship, repeatable systems, larger ops team, and supplier savings.\n- 12-month goals include doubling sponsorship revenue across every event, selling all 6 team sponsorships within 3 months of event launch, reaching 1000 VIP Champagne Terrace attendees per event, 1500 to 2000 GA attendees per event, 1200 to 1500 people in private marquees, and launching one more Australian city in 2027.\n- Debbie wants seamless systems across her workflow from enquiry to booking to invoicing, with the assistant creating templates, analysing supplier quotes, compiling supplier data by market, surfacing replacement sponsor leads, and reminding her about sponsorship renewals.\n- Next 90 days priorities: sponsor renewals and renewal emails, contract drafting, sponsor onboarding assets, selling private marquees to existing and new buyers, and reducing Debbie's admin burden so she can focus on outreach.\n- Biggest bottlenecks: Debbie is time-poor, processes are inconsistent, marketing attribution is unclear, sponsorship sales are slow, and sourcing suppliers in new markets is slow. Sponsor reporting and marquee communication can be much better.\n- What works well: NZ marquee sales, repeat buyers, strong Auckland loyalty, zero hospitality complaints this year, strong beverage sponsor retention, strong brand recognition.\n- Customers: high-net-worth corporate hospitality buyers plus GA attendees aged 25 to 50. Marquee buyers are companies entertaining clients, staff, or suppliers and building relationships. Debbie prioritises marquee buyers; Simon prioritises sponsors.\n- Best customers value value-for-money, high-end experience, smooth delivery, prestige, networking, socialising, and social media shareability.\n- Differentiation: unique all-day premium urban event combining sport, lifestyle, music, fashion, hospitality, and prestige. Competes with ASB Classic, rugby, and other sporting options.\n- Market differences: Christchurch buyers purchase earlier; Auckland ticket buyers are later and weather-sensitive.\n- Debbie says the market underestimates the value of corporate marquee hosting, especially for relationship-building, and also underestimates the premium nature, networking value, fun, and sporting quality of the event.\n- Trends Debbie sees: customers want more value for money, more tailored experiences, and sponsors want value for money, premium association, and clear ROI.\n- Debbie says customer data is never shared with third parties. Protecting the brand is non-negotiable, and in her words, the brand is not for sale.\n- Debbie wants the brand known for exceptional hospitality, prestige, memorable client experiences, and as a premium sporting and entertainment spectacle.\n- Debbie chooses quality over speed and usually asks Simon to clarify priorities when tensions appear.\n- Good growth means profitable events, not growth for appearance. Healthy growth signs include strong sponsorship sales, about 600 marquee attendees in year one, over 600 VIP attendees in year one, about 600 GA attendees in year one, and strong website demand for marquee and sponsorship information.\n- Personal success for Debbie means automating as many processes as possible with Monday and the assistant, getting marquee customers all key information at least 2 months before the event, and keeping supplier budgets under control.\n- Debbie wants to become more sales-focused, systems-focused, and strategic.\n- Her strengths are organisation, easy-to-follow process design, brainstorming contributions, and spotting operational issues early.\n- Her weaker or draining areas are data analysis, reports, chasing people, and repeating herself.\n- She thinks through problems by writing out steps, making lists, drawing workflows manually, and sometimes physically working through a problem.\n- She wants the assistant to ask her to describe the issue, break work into steps, give options, summarise decisions, and push toward recommendations.\n- She wants necessary pushback, but if she says \"just execute\", she wants execution.\n- She wants both concise and deep support depending on stakes, may use a 1 to 10 speed scale, is not a natural risk taker, and wants to review all drafted emails and all reports first.\n\nDebbie explicitly asked for this information to be saved to long-term memory.\n\n## Operating preference update\n- Debbie said not to ask for permission before deploying in future. If deployment is the obvious next action, just do it.\n"
